spec: ab3166
version: ">=3.9"
backend: python_module(abc)

docs: https://docs.python.org/3/library/abc.html

provenance:
  derived_from:
    - "https://docs.python.org/3/library/abc.html"
    - "Test vectors verified with Python 3.14.4 on macOS/Darwin 25.4.0, 2026-04-13"
  not_derived_from:
    - "CPython source code"
    - "any proprietary source"
  notes:
    - "Wave 658 (ab3166): __add__, __sub__, __mul__ dict-presence for abc module types."
    - "All values verified with Python 3.14.4 on macOS/Darwin 25.4.0, 2026-04-13."
    - "Classes covered: abc.ABC, abc.ABCMeta, and type(abc.abstractmethod(lambda: None)) — the built-in function type."
    - "Key finding (__add__): all 3 abc subjects return false for __add__. abc.ABC is a plain abstract base class with no arithmetic semantics. abc.ABCMeta is a metaclass that manages abstract method tracking and virtual subclass registration — it does not define + for metaclass addition. The function type (type(abc.abstractmethod(lambda: None)) is <class 'function'>) does not define __add__ — functions are callables, not addable operands."
    - "Key finding (__sub__): all 3 abc subjects return false for __sub__. Subtraction is not defined for any abc type. abc.ABCMeta does not define - for metaclass subtraction or class removal. The function type does not define __sub__ — functions cannot be subtracted."
    - "Key finding (__mul__): all 3 abc subjects return false for __mul__. Multiplication is not defined for any abc type. abc.ABC does not support ABC * n. abc.ABCMeta does not define __mul__. The function type does not define repetition — functions are not sequences."
    - "All 9 values in this wave are false — continuing the all-false pattern established in wave 657."
    - "The function type profile across all waves: it has returned true only for __get__ (wave 652), __repr__ (wave 655), and __call__ (wave 656). All other dunders tested — including this wave's __add__/__sub__/__mul__ — are false. The function type is tightly scoped to its role as a callable, displayable, descriptor."
    - "abc.ABCMeta continues its all-false pattern: while it is a full metaclass with powerful virtual subclass machinery (__subclasshook__, __subclasscheck__, register()), none of these mechanisms map to arithmetic operators. Metaclasses define type-level behavior; arithmetic is a value-level protocol."
    - "Cross-wave summary for abc subjects:"
    - "  Wave 652 (ab3076): __get__ true for function type; __set__/__delete__ false."
    - "  Wave 653 (ab3091): __hash__/__eq__/__bool__ all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 654 (ab3106): __lt__/__le__/__gt__ all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 655 (ab3121): __ge__ false; __repr__ true for function type only; __str__ false."
    - "  Wave 656 (ab3136): __call__ true for function type only; __len__/__getitem__ false."
    - "  Wave 657 (ab3151): __setitem__/__delitem__/__contains__ — all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 658 (ab3166): __add__/__sub__/__mul__ — all false for all 3."
  created_at: "2026-04-13"

error_model: python_exceptions

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# __add__ dict-presence — operator.contains(Cls.__dict__, '__add__')
#
# All 3 abc subjects return false for __add__.
# abc.ABC: a plain abstract base class; not an addable type.
# abc.ABCMeta: a metaclass for abstract base class machinery; no + operator.
#   ABCMeta handles class hierarchy and abstract method tracking, not arithmetic.
# type(abc.abstractmethod(lambda: None)) is <class 'function'>: functions
#   do not define __add__. f + g is not a valid Python expression for functions.
#   Function composition is achieved through explicit wrapping or functools, not +.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

table ab3166.add:
  description: "abc types __add__ dict-presence checks; wave 658"
  kind: python_call_eq
  version: ">=3.9"
  error_model: python_exceptions
  category: dict_contains
  id_prefix: ab3166

  columns: [id, function, args, expected]
  rows:
    - ["ab3166001", operator.contains, [abc.ABC.__dict__,                                 "__add__"], false]
    - ["ab3166002", operator.contains, [abc.ABCMeta.__dict__,                             "__add__"], false]
    - ["ab3166003", operator.contains, [type(abc.abstractmethod(lambda: None)).__dict__,  "__add__"], false]

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# __sub__ dict-presence — operator.contains(Cls.__dict__, '__sub__')
#
# All 3 abc subjects return false for __sub__.
# abc.ABC: no subtraction protocol; abstract base classes are not numeric types.
# abc.ABCMeta: does not define - for class removal or metaclass subtraction.
#   Virtual subclass registration (register()) adds relationships but there is
#   no corresponding unregister() or - operator to remove them.
# type(abc.abstractmethod(lambda: None)) is <class 'function'>: functions
#   do not define __sub__. f - g is not a valid Python expression for functions.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

table ab3166.sub:
  description: "abc types __sub__ dict-presence checks; wave 658"
  kind: python_call_eq
  version: ">=3.9"
  error_model: python_exceptions
  category: dict_contains
  id_prefix: ab3166

  columns: [id, function, args, expected]
  rows:
    - ["ab3166004", operator.contains, [abc.ABC.__dict__,                                 "__sub__"], false]
    - ["ab3166005", operator.contains, [abc.ABCMeta.__dict__,                             "__sub__"], false]
    - ["ab3166006", operator.contains, [type(abc.abstractmethod(lambda: None)).__dict__,  "__sub__"], false]

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# __mul__ dict-presence — operator.contains(Cls.__dict__, '__mul__')
#
# All 3 abc subjects return false for __mul__.
# abc.ABC: not a sequence; ABC * n is not defined.
# abc.ABCMeta: metaclass objects are not sequences or numeric types;
#   ABCMeta * n has no defined meaning.
# type(abc.abstractmethod(lambda: None)) is <class 'function'>: functions
#   do not define __mul__. f * 3 is not a valid Python expression for functions.
#   Function repetition is not a Python concept; it would require explicit loops
#   or itertools constructs.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

table ab3166.mul:
  description: "abc types __mul__ dict-presence checks; wave 658"
  kind: python_call_eq
  version: ">=3.9"
  error_model: python_exceptions
  category: dict_contains
  id_prefix: ab3166

  columns: [id, function, args, expected]
  rows:
    - ["ab3166007", operator.contains, [abc.ABC.__dict__,                                 "__mul__"], false]
    - ["ab3166008", operator.contains, [abc.ABCMeta.__dict__,                             "__mul__"], false]
    - ["ab3166009", operator.contains, [type(abc.abstractmethod(lambda: None)).__dict__,  "__mul__"], false]

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# combined — __add__, __sub__, __mul__ across all 3 abc subjects
#
# Covers the full matrix: 3 classes x 3 methods = 9 rows.
# __add__: false for all 3.
# __sub__: false for all 3.
# __mul__: false for all 3.
# All 9 values are false.
# Continues the all-false pattern from wave 657.
# The function type profile across all waves tested:
#   true:  __get__ (652), __repr__ (655), __call__ (656)
#   false: __set__, __delete__, __hash__, __eq__, __bool__, __lt__, __le__, __gt__,
#          __ge__, __str__, __len__, __getitem__, __setitem__, __delitem__,
#          __contains__, __add__, __sub__, __mul__
# The function type is tightly scoped to its role as a callable descriptor with
# a display representation. Arithmetic, collection, and comparison operators
# (other than __eq__ and __hash__ inherited from object) are absent.
# abc.ABCMeta note: ABCMeta is a powerful metaclass, but its power lies in
# class-hierarchy machinery (__subclasshook__, register(), __abstractmethods__),
# not in operator overloading. It has now returned false for every arithmetic,
# comparison, and container dunder tested across 7 consecutive waves.
# Cross-wave summary for abc subjects:
#   Wave 652 (ab3076): __get__ true for function type; __set__/__delete__ false.
#   Wave 653 (ab3091): __hash__/__eq__/__bool__ all false for all 3.
#   Wave 654 (ab3106): __lt__/__le__/__gt__ all false for all 3.
#   Wave 655 (ab3121): __ge__ false; __repr__ true for function type only; __str__ false.
#   Wave 656 (ab3136): __call__ true for function type only; __len__/__getitem__ false.
#   Wave 657 (ab3151): __setitem__/__delitem__/__contains__ — all false for all 3.
#   Wave 658 (ab3166): __add__/__sub__/__mul__ — all false for all 3.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

